<TEXT>
two american activists who addressed a 
student rally last week were arrested and ordered expelled for 
taking part in radical political meetings the us embassy said 
today 
the two were identified as susan bailey 31 a secretary in the 
history department at the university of maryland and charles 
scheiner 37 a white plains ny computer salesman 
a us consular officer said ms bailey and scheiner were 
arrested late saturday leaving a meeting with other activitists 
both had tourist visas that prohibited them from any political 
activity said a us official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the two were held overnight by seoul immigration authorities and 
ordered to leave the country for activities inconsistent with 
their visa status 
there were no available flights sunday so us officials said 
the two spent sunday night at the airport and would leave today 
both ms bailey and scheiner spoke to a rally at yonsei 
university aug 15 for some 3000 students assembled to march to 
the border truce site of panmunjom for talks with north korean 
student delegates on reuniting the divided korean peninsula 
the government banned the march and riot police arrested 200 
students 
the americans said they were here at the invitation of the 
korean peace research institute to attend an international peace 
conference 
ms bailey said that she represented the peoples antiwar 
mobilization movement based in washington dc which she described 
as a guerilla movement which wants the government to spend money 
on social causes not defense 
scheiner said he represented a group called national 
mobilization for survival which wanted us military forces pulled 
out of all foreign nations 
