<TEXT>
five years after dissident leader 
benigno aquino was killed the slaying remains unsolved and his 
goal of a peaceful stable democracy unfulfilled in the turbulent 
country now governed by his widow 
on aug 21 1983 the senator stepped from a china airlines jet 
and into philippine history gunned down moments after returning 
from the united states to challenge president ferdinand marcos for 
leadership of the philippines 
the killing outraged the nation and emboldened a fragmented 
opposition paving the way for the uprising that toppled marcos and 
propelled corazon aquino to the presidency on feb 25 1986 
now statues of ninoy the senators nickname stand in 
major cities and the airport where he died bears his name mrs 
aquino has said repeatedly that if it were not for his death she 
never would have risen to power 
but the trial of 40 defendants charged in the assassination 
drags on nearly 16 months after it began bogged down in a complex 
legal system 
in september 1986 the supreme court voided acquittals handed 
down by a marcosera tribunal and ordered a retrial the slow pace 
of the trial typifies the unfinished agenda of an administration 
made possible by the aquino slaying 
the political turbulence that made such a killing possible 
haunts the country for many the lofty hopes that marcos ouster 
alone would restore stability and prosperity have given way to 
frustration 
five years after ninoys death the cory government has become 
the government it warned us against wrote columnist conrado de 
quiros in the philippine daily globe a frequent critic of the 
administration 
critics in the freewheeling manila press often ignore mrs 
aquinos accomplishments preferring instead to hold her to the 
idealistic promises of justice domestic peace and social reform 
she espoused 
despite the insurgency and rightwing coup plots her 
administration drafted a new constitution restored a bicameral 
legislature and held national and regional elections in its first 
two years 
the administration reversed three years of economic decline and 
posted a 55 percent growth in the gross national product in its 
first full year 
but for millions of filipinos more than 60 percent of whom live 
in poverty the slow pace of change has done little to improve 
their daily lives inflation in the manila area triggered by 
increases in prices of food and fuel is approaching 10 percent 
allegations of continuing corruption have been raised not only 
by the press but by manila archbishop cardinal jaime sin the 
countrys best known cleric and an aquino supporter 
communist rebels still wield power in rural areas and urban 
guerrillas have escalated street assassinations in the capital 
itself rightwing death squads have retaliated with their own 
attacks against labor activists and suspected leftists 
if the principal element of aquinos death was violence it 
is only fitting that the people who were shocked by the incident 
and who felt sorry for the late senator should now shun violence 
and work to strengthen the rule of law said the manila bulletin 
in an editorial sunday violence still stalks the land because 
many do not respect the rule of law 
growing disaffection prompted vice president salvador laurel 
this month to accuse the administration of incompetence failing to 
stem the rebellion and tolerating corruption on the scale of 
marcos laurel called on mrs aquino to resign and call new 
elections 
although laurels allegations were similar to those of some of 
mrs aquinos supporters his charges won little public support 
mostly because of the vice presidents reputation as a political 
opportunist 
but if laurels purpose was to jolt cory aquino into waking 
up from her dream presidency and facing the nightmare it has become 
for the filipino people then it certainly deserves a fair and just 
assessment wrote columnist nestor mata in the manila standard 
mrs aquinos strongest supporters frequently dismiss criticism 
as attempts by her opponents to undermine her government 
proaquino columnists claim the latest round of criticism is part 
of a rightwing plot to tarnish her reputation among the public 
under the aquino regime blame is immediately being heaped on 
faceless nameless people who are out to destabilize the 
government wrote columnist ninez cachoolivarez in the 
philippine daily inquirer it is the insecure and paranoid who 
see goblins at every turn 
meanwhile mrs aquino herself has become more isolated from the 
philippine press she rarely gives press conferences or interviews 
recently the presidential palace banned ambush interviews 
where reporters would shout questions at the president as she 
walked to her office every morning 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
robert h reid is chief of the associated press 
bureau in manila 
</TEXT>
